user_location: of Kwik Serv The Woodlands, Texas
review_blob:
Best IPA to come out of Houston. Bold words- I know! lol this brew is fantastic and perfectly comfortable in its cozy nook of classic simplicity. Pours a hazy orange with decent head; lacing is on point. On the nose, floral resin is really all you get. Depending on who you ask, its really all you need! One can detect a mild yet very much consistent floral/hop aroma followed by crisp notes of delicate flower/pine notes and juicy citrus throughout. Has just enough malt structure to support its better half. Clean finish with just enough punch and linger to leave one begging for more. 
Folks, this is truly a special beer in that shes very sessionable. In theory, one could enjoy Yellow Rose on a daily. But then you loose that special, special-ness about her. She is a treat in my book and I treat that with respect. ;)
Cheers!!

user_location: of Kwik Serv The Woodlands, Texas
review_blob: One of my favorite ipas ever! small bouquet with deep citrus. subtle yet prevalent notes of tangerine and grapefruit with some floral tickle. bright, light, and crisp from bite to swallow. short linger leaves one enticed for another sip. excellent all the way around.

user_location: of Kwik Serv The Woodlands, Texas
review_blob: Happen to try this bad boy with the chance of it being as good as Bengali. Resin far exceeded my expectations. my new go too really. very "west coast-y" has a very bright hoppiness to it. crisp, refreshing, bright, herb-pine-citrus top and back bone. leaves a pleasant hop linger. Bravo, Sixpoint!

user_location: of Kwik Serv The Woodlands, Texas
review_blob: Not a huge fan of pumpkin ales but tis the season and this double pumpkin ale is exceptional! big on pumpkin spice from the get go. mellow flavor throughout but still pronounced. has a shade of earthiness if you will, but still a straight shooter with its character. thicker than your average ale, yet still cant touch a stout in that department. smooth finish, not boozy at all. Currently holding on to a few for next year. lets see how graceful time can be to this fat Jack!
beer_name: Samuel Adams Fat Jack Double Pumpkin

user_location: of Kwik Serv The Woodlands, Texas
review_blob: Darn good ipa. worth every cent too, though they sure do add up on this one. nose is citrusy for sure. tastes just as so in addition to some lighter fruits. this brew doesnt molest you with a ton of ibus although very much prevalent in the hops department. goes down ultra smooth but crisp with not too much linger. gives a very profuse mouth feel that is very enjoyable. looks like we gotta winner folks!

user_location: of Kwik Serv The Woodlands, Texas
review_blob: This brew ladies and gentlemen, is what made me a stout lover! balanced and purportionate in every way. the nose could suggests a bit more pine than so. pours a dark brown with a nice ring-y lacing. palate is piney with big caramel and little clove. overall a very well brewed/executed brew. officially a stout lover. can probably tell by my first few reviews. cheers!!

review_blob: This gem caught me by surprise! excellent brew. caramel nut nose, light color and consistency. bit of an oily texture, delicious none the less. very pronounced hazelnut taste. back end still nutty with some caramel/ sweetness. excellent starter brew as not to punchy, but still down right delicious.

review_blob: Poured from a bomber at home. Lots of chocolate in addition to some cinnamon, even less coffee if you will. didnt detect any chili. smooth and creamy with a tan head. can be a bit boozy at high than chilled temp. delicious none the less.
